00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:27.750
PROFESSOR: Today's lecture is
on intermolecular interactions.

00:00:27.750 --> 00:00:32.600
And it's really one of
these favorite topics

00:00:32.600 --> 00:00:37.320
where I can say, well,
this is the origin of life.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:41.150
How do gases actually condense?

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:45.410
And we can build a really,
really simple theory

00:00:45.410 --> 00:00:50.630
for how gases condense
based on what we know,

00:00:50.630 --> 00:00:53.180
based on second order
perturbation theory,

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:55.580
based on some hand-waving stuff.

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:58.340
And it really is
something from nothing.

00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:02.070
But it's also an example of
what we do in physical chemistry

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:07.220
where we explain one phenomenon
by taking something that

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:11.210
seems to be unrelated and
building a model around it,

00:01:11.210 --> 00:01:14.630
and explaining this
surprising thing.

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:19.110
And that's what's
going to happen today.

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:20.720
We'll talk more about that.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:27.760
OK, now last time we talked
about wavepacket dynamics.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:34.060
And so with wavepacket dynamics,
there is first the pluck.

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:37.420
How do you start the system
in some superposition

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:40.300
of eigenstates?

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:48.320
And then there's the evolution
of the pluck, which is usually

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:53.890
some kind of particle-like state
that follows Newton's laws.

00:01:53.890 --> 00:01:59.150
The center of the wavepacket
follows Newton's laws

00:01:59.150 --> 00:02:01.100
for the position
and the momentum.

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:10.470
But if you make a wavepacket
in a real molecule,

00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:14.570
the molecule is going to be
not a harmonic oscillator.

00:02:14.570 --> 00:02:18.590
There will be anharmonic effects
which causes the wavepacket

00:02:18.590 --> 00:02:21.200
to de-phase, but the
center of the wavepacket

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:28.520
continues to move as if it
were in a simple potential.

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:31.130
And it can de-phase, and
rephase, and all sorts

00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:32.180
of complicated stuff.

00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:34.850
And that can be
very interesting.

00:02:34.850 --> 00:02:38.240
Now, when you take this step
from a diatonic molecule

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:41.210
to a polyatomic
molecule, you have

00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:45.560
3n minus 6 oscillators
cohabiting in the same house.

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:47.180
And they're going to interact.

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:51.770
And so if you start
a wavepacket on one

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:54.890
Franck-Condon
bright mode because

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:59.240
of anharmonic interactions
handled by perturbation theory,

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.430
between modes you start to get
this wavepacket leaking out

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:06.110
into other modes.

00:03:06.110 --> 00:03:09.800
And so the expectation
value is going

00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:15.470
to exhibit an oscillating
time dependence associated

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:18.470
with the bright mode and
some of the dark modes

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:21.050
that are anharmonically
coupled to the bright mode.

00:03:21.050 --> 00:03:23.870
And it can get
pretty complicated.

00:03:23.870 --> 00:03:27.580
But you can understand
all of it because you

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:28.930
have perturbation theory.

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:35.920
And so you can say, OK
this time the wavepacket--

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:39.090
some amplitude of the
initial wavepacket

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:41.460
is transferred to
a different mode.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:43.170
And when does that happen?

00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:45.350
Stationary phase.

00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:49.630
It happens at a
particular geometry.

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:52.590
And so you can be
asking, OK, when is

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:54.510
this excitation transferring?

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:55.710
How strongly?

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:59.040
This is a very, very
complete picture.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.860
And it's very much like
classical mechanics

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:03.420
because it's localized.

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:08.820
Then we talked
about Landau-Zener.

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:12.240
And the Landau-Zener is
basically a simple idea

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:16.760
that you also understand
from real life.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:20.920
And it has to do with how does
a wavepacket jump from one

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.310
potential surface to another?

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:27.453
And again, it's
stationary phase.

00:04:27.453 --> 00:04:32.390
At the internuclear distance
of the curve crossing,

00:04:32.390 --> 00:04:35.340
the wavepacket has
to decide which

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:37.140
curve it's going to follow.

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:40.620
And it depends on the
velocity of the packet

00:04:40.620 --> 00:04:45.500
at the curve crossing and the
difference in slopes of the two

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:47.535
paths it has to choose between.

00:04:47.535 --> 00:04:50.400
And all of this is very simple.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:55.290
Now, I am trying to create
an exam problem which

00:04:55.290 --> 00:04:58.080
is related to Landau-Zener.

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.540
And this is hard.

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:05.490
But if I succeed, then
you can expect to see it.

00:05:05.490 --> 00:05:08.550
The last thing I talked
about the last lecture

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:13.000
was the Zewail
pump-probe experiments.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.060
And this is a beautifully
graphical picture

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:20.580
of how do you create
something and then

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.000
probe what's happening.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:27.800
And again, I hope
that I can come up

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:33.170
with something pictorial for
the exam on the Zewail pump.

00:05:33.170 --> 00:05:39.480
OK, now before I talk about
intermolecular interactions,

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:44.120
I want to do a little bit
of tying up loose ends.

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:47.000
You know about non-degenerate
perturbation theory.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:52.100
Now there's another kind of
perturbation theory called

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:53.510
degenerate perturbation theory.

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:01.240
And this is when non-degenerate
perturbation theory

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:13.930
fails because H i j
over E i 0 minus E j 0

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:16.200
is greater than one.

00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:17.519
Well then you've got a problem.

00:06:17.519 --> 00:06:19.310
You can't use ordinary
perturbation theory.

00:06:19.310 --> 00:06:21.940
You have to diagonalize.

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:23.840
You diagonalize it
two by two or you

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:28.990
diagonalize all of the little
cases where this is violated.

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:31.350
That's called degenerative
perturbation theory.

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:33.850
And there is a little
bit of extra recipe

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:37.930
for how do you put information
about remote states

00:06:37.930 --> 00:06:41.130
into the part of the
Hamiltonian you diagonalize?

00:06:41.130 --> 00:06:43.120
That's called a Van
Vleck transformation,

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:45.830
and I'm not going
to talk about it.

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:49.930
But basically you fix things
up by diagonalizing two

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:52.090
by two or three by three.

00:06:52.090 --> 00:06:55.160
And then do ordinary
perturbation theory.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:56.704
And then there's variational.

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:06.220
The variational
model is something

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:12.130
we've used mostly in a
minimum basis set for talking

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:15.800
about the atomic molecules.

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:21.290
And in the variational
model, we minimize energies

00:07:21.290 --> 00:07:25.160
by optimizing
mixing coefficients.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:34.220
Now, perturbation theory is
implicitly an infinite basis.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:36.680
Usually the infinity
doesn't matter

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:39.470
because the interesting
stuff comes in

00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:42.680
from relatively
low-lying levels.

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:45.860
And the infinite number
of very far away levels

00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:49.520
just modifies the energy
levels a little bit,

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:52.050
and you don't have
to worry about it.

00:07:52.050 --> 00:07:57.640
The variational method, you
choose your own basis set.

00:07:57.640 --> 00:08:00.800
Now, the choice of
basis set is frequently

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:02.720
dictated by convenience.

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:09.680
And the basis set is often not
very large or not orthonormal.

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:12.710
And so there are
problems with how

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:15.650
do we deal with
basis functions which

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:20.150
are not orthonormal, especially
not orthogonal to each other?

00:08:20.150 --> 00:08:22.040
And there is a
transformation that you

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:24.860
can do to make that work out.

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:27.890
I mean, the problem
is basically--

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:35.990
the secular equation is this
for the variational method.

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:41.510
And this is the overlap matrix.

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:46.550
And the overlap matrix
is not the unit matrix.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:50.270
We have what's called the
generalized variational

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:51.410
calculation.

00:08:51.410 --> 00:08:53.270
And there are methods
for handling that.

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:57.520
And I have often introduced
those methods on a final exam.

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:03.380
Those are just statements.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:09.320
OK, so variational
is not guaranteed

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:12.900
to give the exact answer.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:17.310
And it can't if you don't
use an infinite basis.

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:20.909
Perturbation theory implicitly
uses this infinite basis.

00:09:20.909 --> 00:09:22.950
And you should feel
confident that you're getting

00:09:22.950 --> 00:09:25.070
close to the right answer.

00:09:25.070 --> 00:09:31.015
And you can know what sort
of errors you're making.

00:09:31.015 --> 00:09:33.030
OK, yes?

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:34.910
AUDIENCE: When you go
to very high orders

00:09:34.910 --> 00:09:36.930
in perturbation theory,
your convergence

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:38.787
is not necessarily better--

00:09:38.787 --> 00:09:39.870
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:41.060
AUDIENCE: --on the
real solutions.

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:41.550
PROFESSOR: OK, but that's--

00:09:41.550 --> 00:09:43.133
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
when to cool it?

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:49.920
PROFESSOR: This is-- the
problem there is that you cannot

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:55.630
include correlation in
perturbation theory.

00:09:55.630 --> 00:09:59.510
And so there are
things that are outside

00:09:59.510 --> 00:10:07.420
of the network of things
that I've described.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:10.650
And so correlation effects
where the particles

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:14.040
can move in some way that
they know about each other.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:18.000
That's very difficult to build
in via perturbation theory.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.400
But when we don't
have correlation,

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:23.130
length perturbation
theory makes an error.

00:10:23.130 --> 00:10:25.770
And you know how
big that error is.

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:35.390
OK, and then we know that we
can diagonalize the matrix

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:39.590
by some kind of
unitary transformation.

00:10:39.590 --> 00:10:48.930
And the columns of T dagger
are the eigenvectors.

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:55.150
And the rows of T
are the inverse--

00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:59.030
rows of T dagger or the
columns of T are the inverse.

00:10:59.030 --> 00:11:02.200
And so if you want to
make a wavepacket where

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:09.280
you have some additional
state to equal 0,

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.430
you want to express that
as a linear combination

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:14.440
of eigenstates.

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.937
And this sort of transformation
provides that information

00:11:17.937 --> 00:11:19.020
if you know how to use it.

00:11:23.370 --> 00:11:25.910
And you can get
approximations to all

00:11:25.910 --> 00:11:29.780
of these elements of T
dagger from non-degenerate

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:31.520
perturbation theory.

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:34.100
And on the second exam
that was one of the things

00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:35.830
you didn't do very well on.

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:40.670
And so you can see that again.

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:41.170
All right.

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:47.710
OK, so now we're going to
talk about intermolecular

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:51.180
interactions.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:53.130
And up until now,
we've been talking

00:11:53.130 --> 00:11:55.870
about isolated molecules.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:11:58.660
And you have a lot of insights
about how isolated molecules

00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:01.600
work, or at least
what kind of stuff

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:04.510
you need to be able to make
predictions about isolated

00:12:04.510 --> 00:12:05.260
molecules.

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:12.100
And perturbation theory
is a very important tool

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:13.720
in building that insight.

00:12:13.720 --> 00:12:18.160
In almost every problem which is
not an exactly soluble problem,

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:21.220
perturbation theory gives you
at least a hand-waving argument

00:12:21.220 --> 00:12:23.640
for what's going on.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:27.530
Everything we did
with LCAO-MO is really

00:12:27.530 --> 00:12:32.180
based on perturbation theory,
or at least the interpretations,

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:35.810
especially when you go from
homonuclear to heteronuclear.

00:12:35.810 --> 00:12:40.310
And when we talk about what
various orbitals look like

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:42.350
and why they look that way.

00:12:42.350 --> 00:12:47.380
OK, so perturbation theory can
also be used to talk about--

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:52.660
we have two particles,
A and B. And we

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:54.560
have the origin of coordinates.

00:12:54.560 --> 00:12:56.245
And so this is the
coordinate for A,

00:12:56.245 --> 00:13:00.940
and this is the
coordinate for B.

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:05.370
And this is the
interatomic coordinate.

00:13:05.370 --> 00:13:09.390
And so we're interested
in what happens

00:13:09.390 --> 00:13:14.370
as a function of this
interatomic distance.

00:13:14.370 --> 00:13:16.890
And can we use
perturbation theory

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:20.252
to be able to say
something about that?

00:13:20.252 --> 00:13:21.460
And the answer is you betcha.

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:29.000
Because basically we understand
how these two molecules work.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.550
And so we have to somehow
build in some insight

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:37.100
into what is the
interaction between these,

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:41.770
and then use perturbation
theory to quantify it.

00:13:41.770 --> 00:13:44.400
OK, now this is
a situation where

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:52.860
we're going to say atoms A
and B are our field shell,

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:54.460
or whatever you want to call it.

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:56.730
They don't need to
make another bond.

00:13:56.730 --> 00:13:58.990
They're not going to
bond to each other.

00:13:58.990 --> 00:14:01.480
There's no covalent
bond between A and B.

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:07.980
There is no charge on A and
B. There is no donor/acceptor.

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:10.560
All of the things
that we can understand

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:12.830
by looking at
individual systems,

00:14:12.830 --> 00:14:14.760
they are all turned off.

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:19.670
These molecules do
have energy levels.

00:14:19.670 --> 00:14:21.940
And so if we could
find some way to talk

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:27.330
about the weak
interaction between them,

00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:29.690
well then we have the basis
for perturbation theory.

00:14:29.690 --> 00:14:32.360
Because we have weak and
we have energy levels

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:35.750
that we know for
the two molecules.

00:14:35.750 --> 00:14:40.410
And so if we're going to
do perturbation theory

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:42.360
it'll be second order
perturbation theory

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:48.990
because we are going to be
interested in how interaction

00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:52.550
of A with B causes
excited states of B to mix

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:57.150
into B, and vice versa.

00:14:57.150 --> 00:15:00.440
And so one of the things you
know about perturbation theory,

00:15:00.440 --> 00:15:05.170
if you're talking about the
ground state of a system

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:13.034
and you do perturbation
theory, what happens?

00:15:13.034 --> 00:15:14.450
What happens to
the energy levels?

00:15:17.660 --> 00:15:19.450
I mean, you have--

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:21.260
for second order
perturbation theory--

00:15:24.921 --> 00:15:25.420
I'm sorry?

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:27.490
AUDIENCE: Everything
gets-- things

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:31.290
can increase or decrease.

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:35.290
The H term gets squared.

00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:35.938
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:15:35.938 --> 00:15:37.562
AUDIENCE: Some
[INAUDIBLE] information.

00:15:37.562 --> 00:15:41.217
But depending on whether
a level that's lower--

00:15:41.217 --> 00:15:43.550
PROFESSOR: But if we're talking
about the ground state--

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:46.092
AUDIENCE: If it's that ground
state it has to go down.

00:15:46.092 --> 00:15:46.800
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:48.620
And so that's the key.

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:52.850
We know that if we're going to
do second order perturbation

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.370
theory and we're going
to be asking questions

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:58.170
about molecules in
their ground state,

00:15:58.170 --> 00:16:00.120
they're going to be
stabilized by interaction

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:01.710
with other molecules.

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:04.830
It doesn't matter,
as long as there's

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:11.340
no bonding interactions,
or very strong short range

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:14.550
interactions, this
sort of a problem

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:19.310
is guaranteed to give
stabilization of the ground

00:16:19.310 --> 00:16:21.095
state of the system.

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:26.330
And that's really a
surprise, because--

00:16:26.330 --> 00:16:26.860
Yes?

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:28.360
AUDIENCE: You're
treating the system

00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:30.860
as though it has like a ladder
of energies and everything

00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:32.960
is already at its lowest?

00:16:32.960 --> 00:16:33.920
PROFESSOR: Yes.

